# Codebook: Variable Definitions and Coding Decisions

## Corpus Variables

| Variable | Description | Values |
|---|---|---|
| `lang` | L1 background | french, italian, portuguese, spanish |
| `level` | CEFR proficiency level | A1, A2, B1, B2, C1 |
| `level_num` | Numeric CEFR level | 1 (A1) through 5 (C1) |
| `wc` | Word count | Alphabetic tokens only (punctuation excluded) |

## Count Variables

| Variable | Description |
|---|---|
| `raw_mv_into` | Verified instances of manner verb + *into* with spatial Ground |
| `norm_mv_into` | Normalized frequency per 10,000 words |
| `raw_mv_outof` | Verified instances of manner verb + *out of* with spatial Ground |
| `norm_mv_outof` | Normalized frequency per 10,000 words |
| `raw_mv_total` | raw_mv_into + raw_mv_outof |
| `raw_pv` | Verified instances of *enter/exit* with spatial Ground noun |
| `norm_pv` | Normalized frequency per 10,000 words |
| `raw_pv_no_object` | Intransitive *enter/exit* tokens (no overt Ground noun; excluded) |

## Motion Type Classification

Manner verb lemmas are classified as:

- **Self-motion**: the agent's own body crosses the boundary
  - walk, run, jump, rush, sneak, crawl, climb, swim, fly, march, slide, slip,
    stumble, tiptoe, dash, race, sprint, stroll, wander, skip, hop, limp, dive,
    burst, crash (24 lemmas)
- **Caused-motion**: the agent causes another entity to cross the boundary
  - throw, kick, push, pull, hit, toss, roll, drop, pour, drag, chase, bounce,
    shoot (13 lemmas)

## Ground Noun Classification

Ground nouns are classified as:

- **SPATIAL** (keep): genuine bounded spaces — enclosed buildings, vehicles,
  natural spaces, containers, urban spaces, geographic territories, sports bounds
- **BODY** (exclude): body-part nouns (stomach, chest, back, etc.)
- **PERSON** (exclude): animate/person nouns (man, woman, player, etc.)
- **ABSTRACT** (exclude): non-spatial concepts including idioms (play, tears, time, job, etc.)
- **NO_OBJECT** (exclude — path verbs only): intransitive uses with no overt Ground
  noun within the search window

## Path Verb Scope

Only `enter` and `exit` (and inflected forms) are included as boundary-crossing
path verbs. The following were excluded with rationale:

| Verb | Reason for exclusion |
|---|---|
| *leave* | Encodes source, not boundary crossing; extremely frequent in non-spatial uses |
| *arrive* | Encodes endpoint/goal, not boundary crossing per se |
| *depart* | Encodes source, not boundary crossing per se |
| *go in/out* | Highly polysemous; predominantly non-spatial in this corpus |
| *come in/out* | Highly polysemous; predominantly non-spatial in this corpus |

## Intransitive enter/exit

Tokens of *enter* and *exit* without a recoverable direct-object Ground noun
within the 5-token look-ahead window are counted separately as
`raw_pv_no_object` and excluded from all analyses. These accounted for 788
tokens (75.0% of all *enter/exit* tokens) in the present corpus. This exclusion
is conservative: many intransitive uses are genuine boundary-crossing events
(e.g., *she entered and sat down*), but the Ground noun cannot be positively
verified from the tagged text alone.

## Manual Review Files

`manual_review_mv_constructions.txt` and `manual_review_path_verbs.txt` document
all noun-by-noun decisions made during the manual review step, including:
- The decision (SPATIAL / ABSTRACT / BODY / PERSON / TYPO / EXCLUDE)
- The context used to make the decision
- Notes on ambiguous cases

These files provide full transparency on the filtering procedure and allow
independent replication of the Ground-noun classification decisions.

## Misspelling Filter (exiting / exciting)

Six tokens of the form `exiting_VBG` in the Spanish subcorpora were identified
as misspellings of *exciting* rather than uses of the path verb *exit*. These
were identified by context (e.g., *very exiting Hi!*, *job is exiting sometimes*,
*exiting becose i like this page*) and excluded from all counts. This finding
illustrates the importance of concordance review even for apparently
straightforward POS-tagged searches.
